    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-01-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-01-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="16"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d16">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Paris Peace Conference 180.03101/11</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Secretary’s Notes of a Conversation, held in M. <persName
                            corresp="#p_PS1">Pichon</persName>’s Room at the Quai d’Orsay, Paris, on
                        Tuesday, January 21, 1919, at 10:30 a.m.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p rend="right">B.C.–6</p>
                <list type="participants">
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Present</hi>.—<hi rend="italic">America, United States
                            of:</hi> President <persName corresp="#p_WW1">Wilson</persName>, Mr.
                            <persName corresp="#p_LR1">R. Lansing</persName>, Mr. <persName>A. H.
                            Frazier</persName>, <persName>Col. U. S. Grant</persName>, Mr.
                            <persName>L. Harrison</persName>.—<hi rend="italic">British Empire:</hi>
                        The Rt. Hon. <persName corresp="#p_LGD1">D. Lloyd George</persName>, Prime
                        Minister, The Rt. Hon. <persName corresp="#p_BAJ1">A. J. Balfour</persName>,
                        Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs, Lieut.-Col. Sir <persName
                            corresp="#p_HLCSM1">M. P. A. Hankey</persName>, K.C.B., Secretary, War
                        Cabinet, Mr. <persName>H. Norman</persName>, Capt. <persName>E.
                            Abraham</persName>.—<hi rend="italic">France:</hi> M. <persName
                            corresp="#p_CGEB1">Clemenceau</persName>, President of the Council and
                        Minister for War, M. <persName corresp="#p_PS1">Pichon</persName>, Minister
                        for Foreign Affairs, <persName>M. Dutasta</persName>, <persName>M.
                            Berthelot</persName>, Capt. <persName>A. Portier</persName>.—<hi
                            rend="italic">Italy:</hi> Signor <persName corresp="#p_OVE1"
                            >Orlando</persName>, President of the Council, His Excellency <persName
                            corresp="#p_SSB1">Baron Sonnino</persName>, <pb facs="0131" n="19"
                            xml:id="pg_19"/> Minister for Foreign Affairs, <persName
                            corresp="#p_MDJACC1">Count Aldrovandi</persName>, Major <persName>A.
                            Jones</persName>.—<hi rend="italic">Japan:</hi>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MNB1">Baron Makino</persName>, His Excellency
                            <persName>M. Matsui</persName>, <persName>M. Saburi</persName>.—<hi
                            rend="italic">Interpreter:</hi> Professor <persName>P. J.
                            Mantoux</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <p rend="center">13. Bolshevik overtures</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">President <persName corresp="#p_WW1">Wilson</persName>
                    </hi> read to the meeting the telegraphic report annexed (Annex “A”) from Mr.
                        <persName>Butler [<hi rend="italic">Buckler</hi>]</persName>, who had
                    interviewed <persName corresp="#p_LMM1">Litvinoff</persName> in Stockholm.<note
                        n="22" xml:id="d16fn22">The report (not here printed) consisted of Mr.
                            <persName>Buckler</persName>’s two telegrams transmitted by the Chargé
                        in Denmark, nos. 116 and 118, Jan. 18 and Jan. 19, <hi rend="italic"
                            >ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_15">pp. 15</ref>, <ref target="#pg_17"
                            >17</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>(It was agreed that this letter should also be translated and discussed at the
                    afternoon meeting.)</p>
                <p>14. …</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <dateline rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Villa Majestic</hi>, <lb/>
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-01-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 21, 1919</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
